SIMPLE: stricture
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stricture
<hw>Stric"ture</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>strictura</ets> a contraction, from <ets>stringere</ets>,
<ets>strictum</ets>, to draw tight: cf. F. <ets>stricture</ets>. See
<er>Strict</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Strictness.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A man of <qex>stricture</qex> and firm abstinence.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A stroke; a glance; a touch.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir M. Hale.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A touch of adverse criticism; censure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[I have] given myself the liberty of these <qex>strictures</qex>
by way of reflection on all and every passage.</q>
<rj><qau>Hammond.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A localized morbid contraction of
any passage of the body. Cf. <cref>Organic stricture</cref>, and
<cref>Spasmodic stricture</cref>, under <er>Organic</er>, and
<er>Spasmodic</er>.</def> <rj><au>Arbuthnot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Strictured</ent>⟦br⟧
